Peter Karp is quite right to insist on clarifying terminology.  The
terminological confusion between "nickname" and "abbreviation"
is significant because it reveals confusion between two distinct
concepts.  While we are on the subject, let me remind members of this
list of a similar distinction: "nickname" vs "alias".  Whereas
there is not universal agreement on the proper choice of terms,
a useful convention is that my NICKNAME for you is an alternative
name I like to use to refer to you, whereas an ALIAS for you is an
alternative name that you would like others to be able to use to refer
to you.  It seems to me that many of the so-called "nickname" examples
(such as the CSNET examples provided by Dennis Rockwell) are really
aliases.  They belong in the global database (CNAME records).
Abbreviations should be handled by user interfaces or name resolvers,
possibly with help from the name server mechanism.
The lookup scheme (1) proposed Peter Karp looks like a nice
way to provide abbreviations.  The "alternative name server" suggestion
proposed by Jon Solomon (or was it Chris Kent?) might be a good way
to provide nicknames shared by a limited community (as in Mark Horton's
"purple" example).

